 in it and relates it to the time at which it was written. Professor Macpherson's introductory and concluding essays expose the roots of some common misconceptions of property, identify current changes in the concept of property, and predict future changes. Macpherson argues that a specific change in the concept (which now appears possible) is needed to rescue liberal democracy from its present impasse.Property is both a valuable text on a crucial topic in political and social theory and a significant contribution to the continuing debate  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aProperty. 4aCoursebook. 7aLAW / Property.2bisacsh1 aBentham, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Morris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill Green, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLocke, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacPherson, C.B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacpherson, C.B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarx, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReich, Charles A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRousseau, Jean-Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStuart Mill, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTawney, R.H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVeblen, Thorstein, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262791840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/